"{\"abstract\":\"We study a competition among two contests, where each contest designer aims to attract as much effort as possible. Such a competition exists in reality, e.g., in crowd-sourcing websites. Our results are phrased in terms of the \\u201crelative prize power\\u201d of a contest, which is the ratio of the total prize offered by this contest designer relative to the sum of total prizes of the two contests. When contestants have a quasi-linear utility function that captures both a risk-aversion effect and a cost of effort, we show that a simple contest attracts a total effort which approaches the relative prize power of the contest designer assuming a large number of contestants. This holds regardless of the contest policy of the opponent, hence providing a \\u201csafety level\\u201d which is a robust notion similar in spirit to the max-min solution concept.\",\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"1728945\",\"name\":\"R. Lavi\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1728945\"},{\"authorId\":\"1810690247\",\"name\":\"Omer Shiran-Shvarzbard\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/author/1810690247\"}],\"citationVelocity\":0,\"citations\":[],\"corpusId\":220483393,\"doi\":\"10.24963/ijcai.2020/53\",\"fieldsOfStudy\":[\"Business\",\"Computer Science\"],\"influentialCitationCount\":0,\"is_open_access\":true,\"is_publisher_licensed\":false,\"paperId\":\"019f869fa32665f8eb1524bd0656fa78d493e3e2\",\"references\":[{\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":\"28822311\",\"name\":\"A. Palmieri\"},{\"authorId\":\"1678255\",\"name\":\"A. Lallouet\"}],\"doi\":\"10.24963/ijcai.2017/101\",\"intent\":[],\"isInfluential\":false,\"paperId\":\"a6c40bc4072a3606916b0bb10abee3b24c829f6d\",\"title\":\"Constraint Games revisited\",\"url\":\"https://www.semanticscholar.org/paper/a6c40bc4072a3606916b0bb10abee3b24c829f6d\",\"venue\":\"IJCAI\",\"year\":2017},{\"arxivId\":null,\"authors\":[{\"authorId\":null,\"name\":\"Benny Moldovanu\"},{\"authorId\":null,\"nam